not show any evidence of intracranial haemorrhage or bony fractures. The skin laceration is about to be repaired.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate placement for the first suture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["On the inferior end of the wound","On the most superficial part of the wound","On the deepest part of the wound","On the vermillion-cutaneous border","On the mucosal-submucosal junction of the upper lip"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAs a general rule of thumb, when repairing any wound that involves two histologically distinct types of tissue, the first suture is placed at the junction between the two types of tissue (\u003Cstrong\u003Ethe vermillion-cutaneous border\u003C/strong\u003E). This is essential as to provide the patient with the best cosmetic and functional outcome. This is especially relevant for a wound involving a cosmetically important area such as the face or involving a highly mobile structure such as the eyelids or the mouth. Keeping in mind that traumatic wound cases are generally less regular and usually accompanied by tissue swelling and edema, it would be very difficult to make sure that the contour of the border of the lip is maintained If the wound repair was started at any other point. Therefore, to yield the best cosmetic and aesthetically appropriate outcome, the first suture is placed at the borderline between the vermillion and the adjacent skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter placing that first suture, more sutures could be placed to repair the rest of the wound. Typically if the wound is very deep or is full thickness, then deep tissue interrupted sutures are necessary to provide appropriate coaptation of the wound and equal distribution of the tension on all layers of the wound. Next, interrupted superficial sutures could be placed to repair the skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMucosal sutures are not necessary as the mucosa heals quite well spontaneously provided that other layers have been adequately repaired (muscles, skin).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["When repairing any wound that involves two histologically distinct types of tissue, the first suture is placed at the junction between the two kinds of tissue.","The vermillion-cutaneous border is a critical landmark in lip laceration repair to ensure optimal cosmetic and functional outcomes."],"references":["Forsch RT, Little SH, Williams C. Laceration Repair: A Practical Approach. Am Fam Physician. 2017 May 15;95(10):628-636. PMID: 28671402. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28671402/","Campo TM. Lip Laceration and Vermilion Border Repair. Adv Emerg Nurs J. 2021 Jul-Sep 01;43(3):206-211. doi: 10.1097/TME.0000000000000356. PMID: 34397497. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34397497/","Espinosa MC, Hohman MH, Sivam S. Oral and Maxillofacial Surgery, Facial Laceration Repair. [Updated 2023 May 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK570584/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63527"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11895"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63527"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T13:46:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T13:47:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4492"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78105"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}}